scenario_purpose: The European Interoperability Framework(EIF) provides guidance to public administrations on how to improve governance of their interoperability activities, establish cross-organisational relationships, streamline processes supporting end-to-end digital services, and ensure that existing and new legislation do not compromise interoperability efforts.This CAMSS Scenario allows to assess the compliance of interoperability specifications with the EIF. The objective of the obtained assessment is to determine the suitability of the assessed interoperability specification for the delivery of interoperable European public services.
criterion_description: The standard or specification has been included in a national catalogue from a Member State whose NIF is fully aligned with at least 4 out of 5 sections of the EIF according to NIFO factsheets.
statement:
PDF is included in 3 national catalogues of recommended specifications. They belong to the Netherlands, Spain, and Estonia. The National Interoperability Framework (NIF) of these Member States is fully aligned with at least 4 out of 5 sections of the European Interoperability Framework (EIF) according to the National Interoperability Framework Observatory (NIFO) factsheets.
See:
https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/collection/common-assessment-method-standards-and-specifications-camss/camss-list-standards
https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/collection/national-interoperability-framework-observatory-nifo/nifo-factsheets

criterion_description: All stakeholders have the opportunity to contribute to the development of the specificationÂ
statement:
ISO has defined a clear procedure to develop its standards. It consist in a 6-steps process where only the full members can participate and influence the development of ISO standards. Individual or organisations cannot be part of the ISO Member bodies, however, ISO has a wide network around the globe in order to capture information from the maximum stakeholders possible. 

Technical committees are in charge of the development of the standards. ISO has defined the roadmap of standards, it is composed of 6 steps as before said.

For the approval of an standard the two thirds majority of P-members of TS is needed. If the result is negative, the document is returned to TC/SC for further studied.  

See: 
http://www.isotc292online.org/projects/iso-process/

criterion_description: The standard or specification is sufficiently mature and has sufficient market acceptance for its use in the development of products and services.
statement: The ISO specifications are published to be able to respond to a market need which represent a consensus of an expert group. It was launched initially by Adobe in 1993 as a proprietary solution but free of charge. In July 1st, 2008 PDF became an Open Standard published by ISO. In addition, PDF is highly adopted as a document format for exchange information, which is technological independent. These facts demonstrate the maturity and market acceptance for its use in the development of products and services.
